		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Idealism</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">This article is about the philosophical notion of idealism.  For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Idealism_(disambiguation)" title="Idealism (disambiguation)">Idealism (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p><b>Idealism</b> is the philosophical theory that maintains that the <a href="/wiki/Ultimate" title="Ultimate">ultimate</a> nature of reality is based on mind or ideas. It holds that the so-called external or "real world" is inseparable from mind, consciousness, or perception.</p>
<p>In the <a href="/wiki/Philosophy_of_perception" title="Philosophy of perception">philosophy of perception</a>, idealism is contrasted with <a href="/wiki/Philosophical_realism" title="Philosophical realism">realism</a> in which the external world is said to have a so-called <a href="/wiki/Absolute" title="Absolute">absolute</a> <a href="/wiki/Existence" title="Existence">existence</a> prior to, and independent of, knowledge and consciousness. <a href="/wiki/Epistemology" title="Epistemology">Epistemological</a> idealists (such as <a href="/wiki/Kant" title="Kant" class="mw-redirect">Kant</a>), it is claimed, might insist that the only things which can be directly <i>known for certain</i> are just ideas (<a href="/wiki/Abstraction" title="Abstraction">abstraction</a>).</p>
<p>In the <a href="/wiki/Philosophy_of_mind" title="Philosophy of mind">philosophy of mind</a>, idealism is contrasted with <a href="/wiki/Materialism" title="Materialism">materialism</a>, in which the ultimate nature of reality is based on physical substances. Idealism and materialism are both theories of <a href="/wiki/Monism" title="Monism">monism</a> as opposed to <a href="/wiki/Dualism_(philosophy_of_mind)" title="Dualism (philosophy of mind)">dualism</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pluralism_(metaphysics)" title="Pluralism (metaphysics)" class="mw-redirect">pluralism</a>.</p>
<p>Idealism also refers to a tradition in Western thought that represents things in an ideal form, or as they ought to be rather than as they really are, in the fields of ethics, morality, aesthetics, and value.</p>
